So, just to tell you, I am not dead. But since many/ all who read this have myspace, they know for sure that I am still breathing (sadly). So I am down in Cali visiting friends and so far this trip has only had 3 good days, 4 shitty days, and only 2 left to go. Yeah, the shitty ones will win sadly. Leslie forgot to get days off from work so every time she has to work, I am stuck and none of my other friends are ever free. I was supposed to hang out with Jeff tonight after he got off from work but his gf showed up so of course I am non existent. Yeah, for being one of my best friends, you think he would tell her that he already made plans to hang out with me when she called him... shows how important I am. Leslie has been trying to make up for the lack of time she can spend with me but everyone is busy whenever I will be alone. This just fucking sucks. It is really making me question who my friends are and if I wanna move back here. For all the homesickness I have felt, it isn't what it's cracked up to be. I guess it will be another year and a half before I am here again, I wonder if anyone will even care at that point...

So, I have been driving a lot from Seattle to Anacortes at random times of the day and night to avoid traffic and no matter how clear it is, there are still people who annoy the shit out of me. 

- Those people who actually go a max of 5 mph over the speed limit in the fast lane need to be shot. I cannot stand them. It's the inner most lane, it's supposed to be the fastest lane and yet they wont go over 65! WHAT THE FUCK!

- The bastards in the huge pick up trucks that can't stay in their own lanes. It's like impossible for them to to stay in the lines, they are always going over them or riding on them at all times. 

- The people who change lanes infront of you that are going 10mph slower than you. Whatever happened to looking before you change lanes? I didn't have to take the driving test when I moved here but I am pretty sure that it's still required to check your mirrors and blind spots before getting over.

- The people who wait forever at stop signs. Come on, you just stop, look for other cars then go. What's so fucking hard about that? I am sick of people sitting there for a couple of minutes like they are just waiting for another car to come. 

- The people who will ride their breaks downhill so they don't go a single mile per hour above the speed limit. When it's fucking 2am and there's no one out, you can go 35 in a 30, no one cares! 

 - Slow mother fucking speed limits. What the fuck? I can understand going 35 in a major city cuz people are jumping out all the time, but in a smaller city that has a two lane in each direction main street, does the speed limit really need to be 25? Come on people, get the stick out of your ass.

- People going under the speed limit when it is actually a good speed. Between Everett and Mount Vernon when you are cruising on the I-5, it's a 70 speed limit, yet I always see people going 60 still. COME ON! As sad as this sounds, but the few times I actually go the speed limit, I am still passing everyone out there.

Man I miss SoCal speeding, that's always fun.

So once again I am sick, who could have guessed right? I went to the doctor today and she said I have severe strep. Yeah, that's fun. So all weekend it has been getting worse and worse. I have been sleeping constantly or feeling like shit. Yesterday my parents tried to make me eat mashed potatoes but I started crying too much so I gave up. My entire body has been aching for days now and I haven't been able to really speak for a couple of days. This morning I wasn't able to even keep water down. So far I have puked 7 times today but right now my stomach is allowing water and even some gatorade so I happy. Puking sucks. This is one of those times when I am really happy that my parents are retired cuz they can take care of me. Both of them went to the doctor's with me, I almost puked when she took the culture from my tonsils then I have to go get blood drawn for the mono test and that made me almost pass out because I was so dehydrated. We ended up getting a wheelchair to get me out to the car then I puked again once we got home... yes... this is so fun. I love digestive pyrotechnics. My poor sick ass... maybe by 10 I'll be able to eat some oatmeal or something. Oh yes, these are the days of our lives...

Our lives are so fickle. In an instant they are gone, no goodbye, no next day, no last breath. February is my month of mourning. I have lost so many people I love this month, so many that I don't even list them on calendars, in my journals, or even speak their names anymore. In these past few years I have learned so much about life as many of my friends have lost their own. I could say it's not fair, it's not right, but it's life. We all die, some just sooner than others. Cruel as it is, our mortality is our greatest weakness. Everything we do is a risk, simply breathing can kill you, yet we do it all. We go on with our lives and ignore it all. I never really had that luxury of of not knowing death. To this day my dad pities me for the loss I have experienced during my short existence. Shit happens. To all those I did not name, you aren't forgotten, you never will be.

The following is supposedly an actual question given on a University 
of Washington chemistry mid-term. The answer by one student was so 
"profound" that the professor shared it with colleagues via the 
Internet, which is why we now have the pleasure of enjoying it. 

Bonus Question: Is Hell exothermic (gives off heat) or 
endothermic (absorbs heat)? 

Most of the students wrote proofs of their beliefs using Boyle's Law 
(gas cools when it expands and heats when it is compressed) or some 
variant. 

One student, however, wrote the following: 

First, we need to know how the mass of Hell is changing in time. So 
we Need to know the rate at which souls are moving into Hell and the 
rate at which they are leaving. I think that we can safely assume 
that once a soul gets to Hell, it will not leave. Therefore, no 
souls are leaving. 

As for how many souls are entering Hell, let's look at the different 
Religions that exist in the world today. Most of these religions 
state that if you are not a member of their religion, you will go to 
Hell. Since there is more than one of these religions and since 
people do not belong to more than one religion, we can project that 
all souls go to Hell. 

With birth and death rates as they are, we can expect the number of 
souls in Hell to increase exponentially. Now, we look at the rate of 
change of the volume in Hell because Boyle's Law states that in 
order for the temperature and pressure in Hell to stay the same, the 
volume of Hell has to expand proportionately as souls are added. 

This gives two possibilities: 

1. If Hell is expanding at a slower rate than the rate at which 
souls enter Hell, then the temperature and pressure in Hell will 
increase until all Hell breaks loose. 

2. If Hell is expanding at a rate faster than the increase of souls 
in Hell, then the temperature and pressure will drop until Hell 
freezes over. So which is it? 

If we accept the postulate given to me by Teresa during my Freshman 
Year that, "it will be a cold day in Hell before I sleep with you, 
and take into account the fact that I slept with her last night, 
then number 2 must be true, and thus I am sure that Hell is 
exothermic and has already frozen over. 

The corollary of this theory is that since Hell has frozen over, it 
follows that it is not accepting any more souls and is therefore, 
extinct...leaving only Heaven thereby proving the existence of a 
divine being which explains why, last night, Teresa kept shouting 
"Oh my God."
